Every time a parent component renders, a new object literal is created in memory. Even if the values are identical, it's a *different object reference*. React uses reference equality by default, so it sees `{ color: 'red' }` on render 1 as different from `{ color: 'red' }` on render 2.

If the child component is doing strict comparisons or dependency arrays, it treats the prop as changed and re-renders unnecessarily.

